[2025-10-04 15:00:50,179] [[33m WARNING[0m]: We did not manage to extract a prediction in the correct format. Gold: ['A'], Pred: ['Statement 1: Every group of order \\( p^2 \\) where \\( p \\) is prime is Abelian.\n\nThis statement is **True**. \n\nAccording to the Fundamental Theorem of Finite Abelian Groups, every finite abelian group of order \\( p^2 \\) (where \\( p \\) is a prime number) is isomorphic to either \\( \\mathbb{Z}_{p^2} \\) or \\( \\mathbb{Z}_p \\times \\mathbb{Z}_p \\). Both of these groups are Abelian.\n\nStatement 2: For a fixed prime \\( p \\), a Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroup of a group \\( G \\) is a normal subgroup of \\( G \\) if and only if it is the only Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroup of \\( G \\).\n\nThis statement is **False**.\n\nThe condition for a Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroup to be normal is that it is the only Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroup. The converse is not true. If a Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroup is normal, it does not necessarily mean it is the only Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroup; it could still be part of a larger set of normal Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroups. The uniqueness of Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroups is a necessary condition for a Sylow \\( p \\)-subgroup to be normal, but not a sufficient one.'] (dynamic_metrics.py:246)[0m
[2025-10-04 15:00:50,182] [[33m WARNING[0m]: We did not manage to extract a prediction in the correct format. Gold: ['B'], Pred: ['To determine the generator for the finite field \\(\\mathbb{Z}_{11}\\), we need to find a number \\(g\\) in \\(\\mathbb{Z}_{11}\\) such that the smallest set of powers of \\(g\\) that covers all the non-zero elements of \\(\\mathbb{Z}_{11}\\) are distinct. This means that the set \\(\\{g^1, g^2, g^3, \\ldots, g^{10}\\}\\) modulo 11 should be the set \\(\\{1, 2, 3, \\ldots, 10\\}\\).\n\nWe will check each option to see if it is a generator.\n\n**Option A: \\(g = 1\\)**\n\\[1^1 = 1\\]\n\\[1^2 = 1\\]\n\\[1^3 = 1\\]\n\\[\\vdots\\]\nThe set \\(\\{1, 2, 3, \\ldots, 10\\}\\) is not covered, so 1 is not a generator.\n\n**Option B: \\(g = 2\\)**\n\\[2^1 = 2\\]\n\\[2^2 = 4\\]\n\\[2^3 = 8\\]\n\\[2^4 = 16 \\equiv 5 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[2^5 = 10\\]\n\\[2^6 = 20 \\equiv 9 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[2^7 = 18 \\equiv 7 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[2^8 = 14 \\equiv 3 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[2^9 = 6\\]\n\\[2^{10} = 12 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{11}\\]\nThe set \\(\\{2, 4, 8, 5, 10, 9, 7, 3, 6, 1\\}\\) covers all the non-zero elements of \\(\\mathbb{Z}_{11}\\), so 2 is a generator.\n\n**Option C: \\(g = 3\\)**\n\\[3^1 = 3\\]\n\\[3^2 = 9\\]\n\\[3^3 = 27 \\equiv 5 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[3^4 = 15 \\equiv 4 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[3^5 = 12 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{11}\\]\nThe set \\(\\{3, 9, 5, 4, 1\\}\\) does not cover all the non-zero elements, so 3 is not a generator.\n\n**Option D: \\(g = 4\\)**\n\\[4^1 = 4\\]\n\\[4^2 = 16 \\equiv 5 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[4^3 = 20 \\equiv 9 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[4^4 = 18 \\equiv 7 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[4^5 = 14 \\equiv 3 \\pmod{11}\\]\n\\[4^6 = 12 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{11}\\]\nThe set \\(\\{4, 5, 9, 7, 3, 1\\}\\) does not cover all the non-zero elements, so 4 is not a generator.\n\nTherefore, the generator for the finite field \\(\\mathbb{Z}_{11}\\) is \\(2\\).\n\nThe answer is: \\boxed{B}'] (dynamic_metrics.py:246)[0m
