.0 \\times 10^{22} \\), and \\( c = -2.367 \\times 10^{22} \\):\n\\[ x = \\frac{-3.0 \\times 10^{22} \\pm \\sqrt{(3.0 \\times 10^{22})^2 - 4 \\cdot 0.5 \\cdot (-2.367 \\times 10^{22})}}{2 \\cdot 0.5} \\]\n\\[ x = \\frac{-3.0 \\times 10^{22} \\pm \\sqrt{9.0 \\times 10^{44} + 4.734 \\times 10^{22}}}{1} \\]\n\\[ x \\approx \\frac{-3.0 \\times 10^{22}}{1} \\]\n\nThis indicates that \\( x \\) is very small compared to \\( 0.789 \\), so the approximation \\( 0.789 - x \\approx 0.789 \\) is valid. Therefore:\n\\[ K_p = \\frac{0.5x^2}{0.789} \\]\n\\[ 3.0 \\times 10^{22} = \\frac{0.5x^2}{0.789} \\]\n\\[ 0.5x^2 = 3.0 \\times 10^{22} \\times 0.789 \\]\n\\[ 0.5x^2 = 2.367 \\times 10^{22} \\]\n\\[ x^2 = 4.734 \\times 10^{22} \\]\n\\[ x = \\sqrt{4.734 \\times 10^{22}} \\approx 6.88 \\times 10^{11} \\]\n\nThis value of \\( x \\) is still very large, indicating that the partial pressure of \\(\\text{O}_2\\) is effectively zero at equilibrium. Therefore, the partial pressure of \\(\\text{O}_2\\) at equilibrium is very close to zero.\n\nGiven the options, the closest answer is:\n\\[ \\boxed{B. 3 \\times 10^{-18} \\text{ mm Hg}} \\]\n\nHowever, it should be noted that the pressure of \\(\\text{O}_2\\) is expected to be very close to zero, not \\( 3 \\times 10^{-18} \\text{ mm Hg} \\). The correct answer should be interpreted as effectively zero, but the closest provided option is \\( B \\).'] (dynamic_metrics.py:246)[0m
