[2025-10-04 15:00:50,489] [[33m WARNING[0m]: We did not manage to extract a prediction in the correct format. Gold: ['D'], Pred: ["To determine the greatest common divisor (GCD) of \\(2^{1001}-1\\) and \\(2^{1012}-1\\), we can use the property of GCD in relation to numbers of the form \\(2^n - 1\\). Specifically, for any integers \\(m\\) and \\(n\\), the GCD of \\(2^m - 1\\) and \\(2^n - 1\\) is \\(2^{\\gcd(m, n)} - 1\\).\n\nHere, we have \\(2^{1001} - 1\\) and \\(2^{1012} - 1\\). The GCD of \\(1001\\) and \\(1012\\) can be found using the Euclidean algorithm.\n\nFirst, let's find \\(\\gcd(1001, 1012)\\):\n\n1. Apply the Euclidean algorithm:\n   \\[\n   1012 = 1001 \\times 1 + 11\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   1001 = 11 \\times 91 + 0\n   \\]\n\n   The remainder becomes zero, so the GCD is the last non-zero remainder, which is 11.\n\n2. Therefore, \\(\\gcd(1001, 1012) = 11\\).\n\nNext, using the property mentioned earlier, we find:\n\\[\n\\gcd(2^{1001} - 1, 2^{1012} - 1) = 2^{\\gcd(1001, 1012)} - 1 = 2^{11} - 1\n\\]\n\nNow, calculate \\(2^{11} - 1\\):\n\\[\n2^{11} = 2048\n\\]\n\\[\n2^{11} - 1 = 2048 - 1 = 2047\n\\]\n\nThus, the greatest common divisor of \\(2^{1001} - 1\\) and \\(2^{1012} - 1\\) is \\(2047\\).\n\nThe correct answer is:\n\\[\n\\boxed{D}\n\\]"] (dynamic_metrics.py:246)[0m
